Washington Times November 4, 1997© <br>
Profiles in courage, closing out of town <br>
By Wesly Pruden,<br><br>
Clever fellows, the Chinese. By the end of his week in the land of Tom Jefferson and Mickey Mouse, President Jiang Zemin seemed to be getting it. <br>
. . . . No thanks go to the wise men who invited him here, and who prostrated themselves in their welcome, not with grief but with greed. The message Mr. Jiang needed to hear seems to have got through to him from a few brave students at Harvard, of all places.<br>
. . . . They greeted him with wonderfully rude slogans and pointedly impertinent placards of the sort he needs to see, but never does: &quot;Down With Jiang Zemin,&quot; and &quot;Down With One-Party Dictatorship!&quot; Mr. Jiang probably wished for a couple of tanks to clear his path, but he seemed to understand that that would have been too much to expect even from President Clinton, who owes him a lot but maybe not that much.<br>
. . . . &quot;Although I am 71 years old, my ears are very sharp,&quot; Mr. Jiang said when he got inside the meeting hall, where a covey of Harvard professors, eager to abase themselves to the correct flavor of dictatorship, waited to enlist as liege men. &quot;While I was speaking I could hear the bullhorns outside.&quot;<br>
. . . . The atrocities that make up the routine of daily business in President Jiang's China are well known in Washington, where there is little patience with anyone who talks about them. What China needs is stability, and our leaders appreciate a man who can impose stability, who understands that a man with a boot on his neck is usually stable enough. There's a certain irony here: When Martha Mitchell remarked, during the VIETNAM WAR, that &quot;after all, Asians don't put as much value on human life as we do,&quot; the poor woman was drawn and quartered by the Nice People in Washington.<br>
. . . . But now the Nice People in Washington are pleased to be saying similarly racist things about the Chinese with whom American businessmen lust to do all manner of sordid business. With a population of a billion-plus and counting, what's one more dead Chinese baby? Henry Kissinger, on the scout for an important ass to kiss, looked euphoric, following President Jiang around town with the short-handled Pooper-Scooper. Nice People like the Doc happily accept Mr. Jiang's disdainful definition of the rights of his own people, that such rights are &quot;situational&quot; and can be defined in whatever way most convenient to the government. If this means torture and hideous death for young women who defy the government's decree against a third child, prison for believing Catholics, and drowning for a young woman detained by police as she was bicycling home from an unauthorized Protestant prayer meeting, well, the brave Nice People in Washington are willing to take that risk.<br>
. . . . The politicians in Washington can't understand why Chinese believers won't practice the nice religious faith they do. Bill Clinton finds religion useful, too: he has misquoted more Scripture than all our other presidents put together, and when he sings in the choir he wants the television cameras there. But you don't see him making a lot of noise about it, or allowing faith to get in the way of the pornographic life on the fast track. And when Tipper, acting on what she learned in Sunday school, scolded Hollywood record producers for their rap to rape by, Al told her quickly enough to put a sock in it. (&quot;Get thee to a Buddhist nunnery if you can't control yourself.&quot;) Why can't those stubborn Chinese Christians learn from the White House example?<br>
. . . . The students at Harvard -- most of them Chinese and not the spoiled brats of the Nice People -- rattled Mr. Jiang enough that he conceded that the Beijing government made &quot;mistakes&quot; and was guilty of &quot;shortcomings&quot; for ordering the massacre in Tiananmen Square in 1989.<br>
. . . . &quot;It goes without saying that naturally we may have shortcomings and even make some mistakes in our work,&quot; he said. &quot;However, we've been working on a constant basis to improve our work.&quot; He's right, it does go without saying, since everybody but the Chinese have been saying it for years.<br>
. . . . A reasonable man can make a plausible case for acting as if the Chinese in Beijing are decent and democratic, even when they are not, in the hope that one day they will emulate the culture and prosperity of their kinsmen in Taipei. The tragedy is that American politicians and the greedy capitalists of the West demand nothing in return. If they had the courage of the demonstrators President Jiang saw at Harvard, Beijing might quickly learn there's a price for cheating, for breaking agreements, for selling arms to thugs and rogues, for emulating Attila the Hun.<br>
. . . . But profiles in courage are no more abundant in America's leadership class than shrewd business acumen, and the whole world suffers.<br>
